As shown in Figure [2](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S2.F2 "Figure 2 â€£ 2 Imperfect Retrieval: The Pitfall of RAG â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models"), although instances from different datasets exhibit different data distributions, imperfect retrieval is prevalent. Specifically, âˆ¼similar-to\\simâˆ¼20% of the overall data have no mentions of the correct answer within any retrieved passage, including 34% on NQ, 18% on TriviaQA, 24% on BioASQ, and 50% on PopQA. This finding also aligns with previous observation on information retrieval (Thakur et al., [2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#bib.bib25)), that highlights that the number of positive passages can be very limited.

Imperfect retrieval leads to RAG failures. We further analyze the relation between retrieval quality and RAG performance. We compare the performance of Claude 3.5 Sonnet, with and without RAG and report the results by retrieval precision in Figure [4](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S4.F4 "Figure 4 â€£ 4.3 Analyses â€£ 4 Experiments â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models"). In general, RAG is helpful when the retrieval precision is not lower than 20%. When the retrieval precision is close to 0, the model with RAG performs much worse than without RAG, indicating that imperfect retrieval augmentation can be the cause of RAG failures. This finding aligns with the previous observation from Yu et al. ([2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#bib.bib42)) that adding more retrieved passages does not necessarily lead to better performance, as the additional passages might reduce the retrieval precision.

Knowledge conflicts widely exist in RAG failures. We provide an in-depth analyses of knowledge conflicts between LLMsâ€™ internal knowledge and retrieved passages from external sources. With Claude 3.5 Sonnet as the LLM, Figure [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S1.F1 "Figure 1 â€£ 1 Introduction â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models") shows that 19.2% of the overall data exhibit knowledge conflicts, where either the answer with or without RAG is correct. Among the conflicting cases, the internal knowledge is correct on 47.4% of them, while the external knowledge is correct on the remaining 52.6%. These results emphasize the importance of effectively combining the internal and external knowledge to overcome the inherent limitation of relying solely on either source. However, previous work (Tan et al., [2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#bib.bib24); Xie et al., [2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#bib.bib33); Jin et al., [2024](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#bib.bib14)) show that LLMs might respond based on misleading information rather than comprehensive understanding of the conflicting knowledge in this context.

3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall
------------------------------------

![Image 3: Refer to caption](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1/extracted/5914248/figure/method_2.png)

Figure 3: Overview of the proposed Astute RAG framework. Astute RAG is designed to better combine the information from the external sources (e.g. web, domain-specific corpora, knowledge bases) and internal knowledge of the LLMs by employing a consolidation mechanism to address the information conflicts, which eventually leads to better quality generated outputs.

We begin with formulating the problem of imperfect retrieval in RAG (Section [3.1](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S3.SS1 "3.1 Problem Formulation â€£ 3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models")). We then provide an overview of Astute RAG, designed to overcome this problem (Section [3.2](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S3.SS2 "3.2 Overview of the Framework â€£ 3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models")). Subsequently, we delve into the three major steps of Astute RAG, including adaptive generation of internal knowledge (Section [3.3](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S3.SS3 "3.3 Adaptive Generation of Internal Knowledge â€£ 3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models")), source-aware knowledge consolidation (Section [3.4](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S3.SS4 "3.4 Iterative Source-aware Knowledge Consolidation â€£ 3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models")), and answer finalization (Section [3.5](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S3.SS5 "3.5 Answer Finalization â€£ 3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models")).

### 3.1 Problem Formulation

Our objective is to mitigate the effects of imperfect retrieval augmentation, resolve knowledge conflicts between the LLMâ€™s internal knowledge and external sources (such as custom/public corpora and knowledge bases), and ultimately produce more accurate and reliable responses from LLMs.

Given a set of retrieved passages from external sources E\=\[e1,â€¦,en\]ğ¸subscriptğ‘’1â€¦subscriptğ‘’ğ‘›E=\[e\_{1},\\ldots,e\_{n}\]italic\_E = \[ italic\_e start\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , â€¦ , italic\_e start\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\_n end\_POSTSUBSCRIPT \], a pre-trained LLM â„³â„³\\mathcal{M}caligraphic\_M (accessible through prediction-only APIs, encompassing commercial black-box ones), and a query qğ‘qitalic\_q, the task is to generate the corresponding correct answer aâˆ—superscriptğ‘a^{\*}italic\_a start\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT âˆ— end\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. Notably, this setting is orthogonal to prior work on improving the retriever, training LLMs, or conducting adaptive retrieval, which are mainly preliminary steps.

### 3.2 Overview of the Framework

Astute RAG is designed to better leverage collective knowledge from both internal knowledge of LLMs and external corpus, for more reliable responses. As shown in Figure [3](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#S3.F3 "Figure 3 â€£ 3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models") and Algorithm [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2410.07176v1#alg1 "Algorithm 1 â€£ 3.2 Overview of the Framework â€£ 3 Astute RAG: Overcoming the Pitfall â€£ Astute RAG: Overcoming Imperfect Retrieval Augmentation and Knowledge Conflicts for Large Language Models"), Astute RAG starts from acquiring the most accurate, relevant, and thorough passage set from the LLMsâ€™ internal knowledge. Then, internal and external knowledge are consolidated in an iterative way, by comparing the generated and retrieved passages. Finally, the reliability of conflicting information is compared and the final output is generated according to the most reliable knowledge.

